segments.text: Double chicken slash S to receive that.
I don't believe we ever did it in our unit.
I know we didn't.
I know we didn't.
So drownouts were considered kind of good fun?
Good bull.
OK, good bull.
Yeah.
Define good bull.
Good bull, I think, to me, was doing something to the upperclassmen.
Now, good bull goes up.
It doesn't come down.
You don't haze a freshman for good bull, I think.
That's my opinion.
Doing something to them.
Because you're also telling them you're important.
Because if they're the attraction of this, and maybe I didn't know it then, but I know it now, that you're paying attention to them, it makes, hey, you must be important.
Or you must have, you know.
And so you didn't want to leave anybody out.
At least we didn't mess them up.
I'm sure there was other kinds of... Could good bull be harmful in school?
No, absolutely cannot be harmful.
Never.
And that's why... You asked me a question and I didn't finish the answer.
It can never hurt anybody.
It can't be... have a financial or harmful effect.
It just...
an action which may cause an embarrassment or a momentary loss of something that they find.
Am I correct that the more nearly original, one of a kind it is, the better good bull it is?
Oh, absolutely.
I'm trying to remember.
There was somebody, very few people had cars up there at the time.
And
There was, someone had a Volkswagen, and I don't know how it was done.
I think it was, I think I was either a freshman or sophomore, but I don't know if I was either a sophomore or junior when this happened, but that car ended up on the third floor inside the dorm.
And they, people actually carried that car around the stairs and up into the dorm.
And you know, that, they didn't hurt anybody, but you can imagine, you walk out and there's your car outside your room.
You know, it's...
But pranks like that, I wish I could remember some more than I may remember some.
What was it like to be a sophomore?
Tell me about sophomore privileges.
Very important position.
I thought I was King Kong.
I got purple stripes.
And I didn't have them long, but I got them.
And I prided myself in my dress and in my hair.
a department of, I never marked the bullring.
I never one time can I remember marked the bullring.
And I got the merits, but not enough to get on the bullring.
I think once I reported it, it was inclement weather and we did something else, which I thought was a terrible waste of time, as times go.
But of course, you know,

People would love to tell you, I think, and I would love to tell you that, boy, you know, I was the freshman's friend, and I really worked on training, but in respect we did, we weren't their friend to speak of, but we were concerned because it was our job to teach them certain things, like how you wear the uniform, how to march.
Sometimes, and I'm not going to say I didn't go overboard, we all went overboard.
That's part of the learning process of
of responsibility and finding the line.
And you've got to cross it to find it sometimes.
And I made a cross because I lost my corporal stripes.
When did you feel, describe for me the emotional circumstance when you officially became a sophomore?
Well, of course, that was at senior review.
And that's when you're officially a sophomore and you start feeling, there's no freshman around, but the juniors then start treating you like a human being.
And do you remember anybody saying or doing anything that made you feel, okay, it's really finally happened?
I suspect that the first sergeant gave us a pep talk about it.
And certainly when we got back, there was a lot of means to align our responsibilities and
and how important it was to be a good sophomore.
But a final review is when you put on your brass and you wear your hat a little different.
And you can call, instead of calling somebody a mystery, you call them by their last name.
And then if their desire to drop handles with you, they do so.
Even though a lot of people drop handles as freshmen.
And those, you call by their first name
Now, I presume that you didn't have any family there for that final review, you're afraid, you're fishing.
Let's jump to academics.
Some special teachers, advisors, counselors that you remember as being important to your academic preparation.
You know, I thought C.K.
English?
English, yeah.
C.K.
Estes.
Estes, yeah, C.K.
He was also the announcer at the football game for so long.
I had English with him as a, I guess as a junior, and he was a very interesting man.
He was just absolutely, where I feel like people are trying to challenge our thinking, and not necessarily our
I mean, we had to write a lot and do a lot of things, but he was just so interesting from being a civil engineering major.
I enjoyed the math courses.
Teddy Hirsch at the time was a TTI.
I think he was working on a doctorate.
And I had a sophomore course with him in something in engineering, and he was really interesting.
Dr. Harrington.
Well, there were two Dr. Harrington at the time.
One of the top hydraulics to us.
Of course, even my brothers had just gone through.
And so they kind of picked on me a little bit from the standpoint of another Fernandez coming through.
Not picked on me, but picked on me fun-wise.
And I felt important them doing that, frankly.
Joe Sorrells in soils was an excellent instructor.
General Buchanan.
Spencer.
He's elderly.
Spencer, yeah.
I remember that he taught us a course, and we were seniors, and starting to think about, hey, what do you do, and what word do you use when you hit your jobs?
You know, those kinds of things.
Let's see.
History.
Haskell, I took, I know, one history course, maybe both, in summer school, where I could concentrate on them.
Because I would go to summer school when I'd go back to Laredo and go to junior college.
I know I took a history course there.
I don't remember taking a history course at College Station.
You said chemistry, math?
Chemistry was challenging.
Who?
Do you remember who it was?
The one I flunked or the one I passed?
I passed chemistry one, and... John Beckham, by chance?
No, I didn't have Beckham.
And then I flunked chemistry two, and then I took it my sophomore year.
And, you know, there's quizzes that float around.
And academically, I probably... Chemistry wasn't my best subject.
And I probably went in with a 70 into the final exam.
And you don't study for chemistry?
What do you do?
So, Halloween is, my dear friend, the Greek from Houston...
He had an old final.
We didn't know where it was from.
We studied that.
And four of us studied it.
I'd probably go to jail today.
But no, it was legal.
They were around.
They were here to criticize.
And we didn't steal it.
But we studied that.
And just in case, we happened to get this exam.
Hey, let's not sit anywhere close together.
So we sat in four different corners.
And just four of us studied it.
Verbatim.
I mean, it was exactly.
I mean, that's the most astonishing thing that ever happened to me.
That's the fault of the faculty member.
I don't know.
I might not have passed the second time he had been there.
He probably said, how did this guy get so smart so quick?
I know he's not.
Do you remember any of the faculty nicknames?
Yeah, in our course of civil engineering, Snuffy Smith.
Why was he called Snowfield?
Oh, I think he had a nasal problem.
I think that's right.
I've seen a book recently where we had some of these nicknames.
And who else was there?
There was another gentleman, such a neat man.
Oh, what a gentleman.
but none other than the nickname.
He just always had such a nice presence about him.
But Dr. Wright was the department chair.
We didn't interact with the department chair a whole lot.
He didn't either.
I never took a course with him.
But... All right, what about over in the Corps area?
Attack officers, commandants?
We had favorite attack officers.
Of course, we had nicknames for them.
There was the Goose, and there was Porky.
The Goose, I'm trying to think of his name, his brother was in our class.
Goose had a brother that was class 59.
And then, I swear, I can't remember the last name.
Give me a chance, when it was Lieutenant Hornstein, I still see Hornstein from time to time.
Who was the commandant then?
Moore?
No, not Moore, excuse me.
Joe...
Joe Davis.
Joe Davis.
Joe Davis.
All right.
Now, do I remember Fighting Joe?
Was that the nickname he had?
He was too high up there for us to get a nickname to.
But one time we were lining up for supper to go to dinner, and of course the goose had a very, well, he was called the goose.
He had a very posture kind of problem that he kind of looked like a goose when the upper half of his body kind of tilted forward.
You know how a goose looks.
And then Porky had obviously the statistics to go with that.
And they were up there and they were calling to, and by that time we were in the Duncan area.
And the steam tunnel, you know, the lid opens up, boom, out comes a pig, out comes a goose, and they just scatter.
The whole court just died laughing.
And boy, they turned red and green and every color in the booklet.
Those were pranks.
They didn't hurt anybody.
That's a good book.
That's a good book.
All right.
Classroom behavior.
What do you, as you look back, what were the unwritten or maybe well understood rules of classroom behavior?
We didn't have a behavior problem in the classroom that I remember.
Did you all go to class regularly?
Absolutely.
Did you stay awake?
Most of the time.
The only time I've had a problem is maybe I was up working all night on a lab or on a problem that we turned in, and many, many times we saw the sun come up.
finishing up a report, because that's a procrastinator.
But we were there, and we were attentive, and the instructors were of quality that I remember.
Were they available when you needed them, if you wanted to see them?
They weren't there ten minutes after the hour.
There was nobody else there to read them.
But if you needed to go see them one-on-one, seek advice, you could find them?
Yes.
You know, I never...
I never had, I never did that.
Maybe I should have.
Maybe I would have gotten out in four and a half years.
But they were, they were certainly, especially when you're in the department.
You know, we took, a freshman took mechanical drawing, took English, math.
See, I was a math whiz.
And I thought, man, this is a piece of cake.
And I almost didn't pass math with a freshman.
I just, I think I took it too lightly.
I posted a .89 my first semester.
And I went up there with, you know, I had pretty good, I had very good high school preparation.
They prepared us excellent.
And I think just, you know, finding, learning how to, number one, schedule one's time and those kind of things.
But it got my attention.
I got on probation the first semester.
Did you have in math square root Jackson or cube root Kent, either one?
No, but I heard of it, yeah.
Let's see, let's go to activities.
YMCA, do you remember?
We didn't do Y.
All right, MSC.
MSC was, because I worked there, and it was... What role did it play in the typical student's life?
Our post office box was there.
Either, well, when we were...
If you lived around Duncan, it was there.
If you lived at the other, it was the one on the corner of Northgate.
But, you know, so you went there.
It was kind of a place between classes.
We didn't really hang out there.
Were you proud of it?
I was, sure.
That was built in 50, right?
Opened in 50, and I was there in 55.
Did you and Wayne Stark ever interact?
I knew him.
I didn't interact with him as I heard he interacted with some tremendous students.
Guy and Hall, did you ever go?
Fantastic.
What was important about Guy?
Well, there were two shows going on.
There was a show on the screen, and there was a show, and the comments of the roommate, and a lot of it.
It was just a fun place to be.
And was the audience almost entirely all students?
Yes.
Do you remember anything ever being said that was bad taste?
No, absolutely not.
Let me just clarify that.
Never any profanity.
And I'm pretty conscious of that, even as a young man.
And our values move around in our...
But for college, the campus of the day, nothing grows.
It was okay.
Do you remember any important lecturers or famous personalities that ever came to?
speak at Guyon?
No, I don't.
And I know there were sometimes religious related activities in Guyon.
We went to, you know, the Catholic Church was very active.
You know, I was so busy when I was a student.
Number one, working.
Number two, playing corps cadets, which probably
If you ask me in what order, that, and then academics.
And then my days were full.
And intramurals.
I loved intramurals.
We did that.
And the core activities and everything.
I didn't have a lot of time.
And I never, to my loss, participated in any of the, I think SCOAN started about that time, if I remember correctly.
And there were other things that were available.
Did you go on weekends?
Did you go to Mass?
Yes.
Where?
At the, what is it, St. Ann's?
St. John's?
I can't remember.
I want to say St. Mary's, but I don't think that's right.
Yeah, I think St. Mary's.
I can't remember the priest's name.
As you recall, a typical Sunday morning, the audience would be made up of what?
Mostly students or half students?
No, there was, there was, we can't identify with a lot of faculty, but there was, especially on weekends, there were a couple there, parents and folks like that.
Of course, at that time, parents didn't come up to the university like we were able to enjoy when our kids were there.
My mother went for my graduation.
The only time she went to the campus.
I don't think my father ever went.
Do you remember religious emphasis week in the spring?
Yes.
Do you remember participating?
Well, it was just like any other week of religion.
We went every Sunday to Mass.
And also, I guess at Mass you see your hometown buddies, but most of them were Catholic.
And we would see each other there.
And Sunday was a softer day than others.
Thank you.
Do you remember any, now as you look back, any life-changing conversation or events during your student years?
Events?
Yeah, where?
Many, many events.
Share some.
It impacted me.
Remember I told you that
the group or the company that had the best General Moore got the top floor.
And when we were juniors, we were on the bottom floor.
And that was humiliation.
Paul Buenas was the first sergeant and
Tommy Lone was platoon leader, and I can't recall who the other one was.
And then we all, we had a meeting the first week of school as juniors, okay?
And you couldn't stand the humiliation of not being the best outfit in that battalion.
So what we did, we set a goal to win general war.
And we said, here, this is how you're graded.
Okay, you're in charge of this, you're in charge of this, you're in charge of that.
You're in charge of intramurals.
And then I became the intramural sergeant.
And we all had a job.
And we were always strong in student leadership.
We didn't have a class that didn't have a vice president, president class.
We motivated our people and they motivated us.
to seek out and to do the kinds of things that interested us.
And we had a program the time before.
And so there's no reason for you to get a forfeit.
The least you can do is show up and represent.
And then if you show up and have a little bit of organization, and that was my job.
And we came in the top 10, both upperclassmen and freshmen, from down in the nobody even noticed.
We came in second in marching.
who came in high in grades.
Bottom line, we wanted to know more.
Now see, that's the kind of thing that I treasure in here.
Do you remember any one-on-one conversations with a faculty member or an advisor that you now realize were important to you?
Not one that just, you know, that I would get to pull, even though they were all
extremely kind and helpful, and they had to be to get me through.
I mean, I know I challenged some of them, but getting back to the General Moore deal, it taught me that I can do anything.
And if you work in a group with someone responsible for something, that you can get a team going and
You may not win that brass ring, but we can sure, by proper planning and hard work, can do anything.
And I was so proud.
It was one of the proudest moments of my life.
You showed that while ago in your response.
Describe, in general, the student body when you were there, economically, geographic origin, ethnic, et cetera.
Economically.

Economically, I guess even though it wasn't important, you could tell who came from a little more affluent family because they might have a car in the parking lot even though there were very few cars.
By and large, were the students rich?
No, I didn't think so.
I would have been surprised if you had said yes.
No, most of us were from small towns and big towns, but just ordinary people.
Ordinary people.
And a high percentage of first-generation college students, I bet.
Frankly, I don't think it was a topic of interest.
I wouldn't be surprised.
I know we were serving the first generation of our family, Brother Gus and Albert and I.
But everybody wore the same uniform, and you really couldn't tell.
And nobody ever flunked it.
You know, flaunted that.
Let's see.

There were, of course, there were no blacks, and there was, there was a, not a handful, there was a considerable number of Mexican-Americans, a lot from Laredo, from San Antonio, and a lot of other areas.
It wasn't, I wasn't the only one there.
Did any, did you or anyone else feel that you were handicapped
in being selected for anything because of your background.
It's a non-factor.
Not to get it or to get it.
I would have been surprised if you had said otherwise.
I know Hector Gutierrez well.
And Hector says the fact that he was corps commander, he said that had nothing to do with my last name, which I say hooray.
Let's see.
Optional student organizations.
Was the singing cadets, were they around then?
They were around.
Did you all have a, to being a singing cadet, was that a plus or a minus for anybody?
You know, they weren't as visible at that time as they are today, even though, well, maybe to where they presented were more visible.
We probably did, it was like those that did it, it was like those in the band, you know,
it wasn't something that was a negative or a positive.
What about the band?
Was that a high prestige?
I'm hesitating because I want to be sure that I think about the question.
You know, even being athletes at that time, you know, I took classes with Richard Gay.
He was a C.E.
major and with a lot of other football players and basketball players.
It was... Did y'all make fun of the band members?
No, absolutely not.
That surprised me when I... And I guess that's probably a good fun, maybe even a little jealousy there.
I hold them in awe.
We were their best supporters.
We never left the stands at halftime.
The band was important to us.
But it wasn't like they were a notch above or a notch below because they were or weren't
What would have been the most notable student leadership position?
In my opinion?
Then and now?
No, then.
Then.
Then and now.
Oh.
Company commander.
Company commander.
That's where the rubber meets the road.
Oh, okay.
Because student body president wasn't a big deal.
It was pretty important.
Was it?
That was, yeah.
Okay.
That was.
But I still, you see, the unit commander is the, at that time, there was three buttons.
And to me, that was the most prestigious.
Yeah, my roommate was student body president.
John Thomas.
Oh, yeah.
One of my roommates.
And...
But we trained and we prepared for those kinds of jobs in my outfit.
And it was part of doing our job.
And we had, you know, we had that year, the class vice president was a member of our outfit.
And like I said, in every class we had somebody from our outfit in one of the four offices.
But I think that the company commander is the most prestigious position.
Let's see.
RVs?
Prestigious.
First real team.
Now, I'm not asking if you were one or not.
I was not.
No, no, no, no, no.
RVs never know what I mean.
They don't have grades.
I'm about to ask them another question.
Were you aware there were any secret fraternities when you were a student?
No, I was not.
No, no, you were not aware?
I was not aware.
Okay.
Because as I've done these interviews, a few people have given me guarded answers.
Yes, they heard about the TTs and the stickers, but...
I haven't gotten any.
I don't know anybody that was in one.
I don't know.
Oh, you know the funny story, if you want to know the funny story.
Please do.
As, because you know, we go to summer camp as juniors.
Okay, I was, I wasn't a hellraiser, but I was, I was active, let me put it that way.
But I was also active in the plus things, and maybe, you know, I lived close to the line, and...
And I was doing a lot of things.
My grades were marginal, but I took corps seriously, even though some of the tech officers in the commandant's office might have said, well, I don't know about him.
But when we went to summer camp, again, you know, play the game.
And I was selected
And you go and you're bunched in with a bunch of people from other schools, St. Mary's, Providence, there was Oklahoma, and we went to Hood.
And I got selected number two.
I was the number two cadet in this company.
But Aggies usually score high.
And the number one cadet, I think it was, it was an Aggie, and I think it may have been Fred Capra.
They do about an alphabet.
But anyway, I was recommended for a distinguished military student.
And I know they had a very good laugh about that in the commandant's office when that recommendation came down.
And I saw the letter, but I didn't have the craze, number one.
But I had the will.
Let's see.
Describe a basketball game in G Raleigh.
Loud, fun.
We had more, we had a large contingent of the band, if I remember correctly.
It was a, it was pretty, it wasn't a skeleton, it wasn't a skeleton band.
And we went, we went to the basketball games.
Do you remember any pranks or jokes at a basketball game?
Any tricks they were played on anybody?
No, no they don't.
I haven't heard of any.
They didn't play a lot of baseball games.
